          "body": "Moab was not a distant abstraction to Jeremiah's audience. Descended from Lot and thus from Abraham's own household (Genesis 19:37), Moab was Israel's nearest Semitic neighbor east of the Dead Sea. The relationship was laced with complicated history: Ruth was Moabite (Ruth 1:4); David sheltered his parents there (1 Samuel 22:3–4); Moabite kings repeatedly oppressed and clashed with Israel (Judges 3:12–14; 2 Kings 3). Yet Moab also scorned Israel, refused hospitality during the exodus (Deuteronomy 23:3–4), mocked Jerusalem's fall (Ezekiel 25:8–9), and — as verse 27 charges — treated Israel as a laughingstock. The oracle therefore carries the particular sting of family betrayal. The prophet who elsewhere weeps over Judah's judgment now presses the same sovereign God's verdict against the nation that had watched Israel fall with contempt."
