          "title": "The wine-on-its-dregs metaphor: complacency as the root of pride",
          "body": "The chapter's most theologically dense image occupies verses 11–13. Moab has been 'at ease since his youth,' settled on its dregs like wine that has never been poured from vessel to vessel. Ancient winemaking required periodic decanting — wine left undisturbed on its sediment retained a harsh, unchanged character, never refined to purity. The metaphor identifies the spiritual mechanism beneath Moab's pride: not sudden arrogance but decades of undisturbed ease that had calcified into settled self-sufficiency. No exile, no humiliation, no upheaval had emptied Moab into a new vessel and purged the sediment. Therefore 'his flavor has remained the same and his aroma is unchanged' (v. 11). God's response (v. 12) is the reversal: He will send those who tip the vessels and shatter the jars. Verse 13 applies the lesson comparatively — Moab's coming shame in Chemosh will mirror Israel's earlier shame in the Bethel calves. Misplaced confidence produces identical humiliation regardless of covenant status."
