          "title": "The eschatological reversal: restoration in the latter days",
          "body": "The chapter's final verse is its most unexpected: 'Yet I will restore the fortunes of Moab in the latter days, declares the LORD.' After 46 verses of unrelenting judgment, this single line opens a completely different horizon. The phrase 'latter days' (acharit hayamim) appears elsewhere in Jeremiah for the eschatological restoration of Israel itself (30:24; 31:33); its application to Moab is extraordinary. Comparable promises appear in 49:6 (Ammon) and 49:39 (Elam), suggesting a pattern: the oracles against the nations are not pronouncements of ultimate and eternal reprobation but of temporal judgment with eschatological hope. Whether these promises were partially fulfilled in the post-exilic mixing of peoples or await a fuller eschatological realization is a matter where evangelical scholars hold different readings — premillennial interpreters tend toward a literal national restoration; amillennial and postmillennial readers see the promise fulfilled through Gentile inclusion in the new covenant community. Both readings agree that the oracle's final word is mercy, not annihilation."
