        "excerpt": "Therefore I will wail for Moab, even for all Moab will I cry out; I will moan for the men of Kir-heres.",
        "body": "This section is one of the most remarkable passages in the entire book of Jeremiah. Having pronounced the verdict (vv. 1–30), God shifts person and register: 'Therefore I will wail for Moab... I will moan for the men of Kir-heres... More than the weeping for Jazer I will weep for you, O vine of Sibmah.' The prophet who weeps throughout his own book (Jeremiah 9:1; 13:17; 14:17) is here channeling the very grief of God over the nation God is destroying. The vine of Sibmah, famous for its abundant tendrils reaching to the sea (v. 32), is ruined — and God mourns the ruin. The gladness and joy removed from the fruitful fields (v. 33), the wine-presses silenced (v. 33), the waters of Nimrim dried up (v. 34) — each agricultural loss is grieved by the One who gave the land its fertility.\n\nThis passage closely parallels Isaiah 15–16, where the prophet similarly mourns the fall of Moab. The literary relationship is almost certainly deliberate: Jeremiah is consciously citing and expanding the earlier Isaiah oracle, showing that God's grief in the eighth century BC has not diminished but intensified as the judgment draws nearer. The flute (*chalil*, v. 36) was the instrument of funeral lamentation in the ancient Near East — its mournful sound is God's own self-description. Both John Calvin and Jonathan Edwards noted that divine impassibility does not mean divine indifference; God is not moved against His will, but He genuinely grieves over the consequences of sin that He has sovereignly permitted and now judges.\n\nVerses 37–39 describe the human mourning rites with ethnographic precision: shaved heads, clipped beards, gashes on hands, sackcloth — the full array of ancient Near Eastern mourning practices (cf. Deuteronomy 14:1; Isaiah 15:2–3). The mourning is universal: 'on all the housetops of Moab and in its streets there is lamentation everywhere.' Verse 38 closes the lament section with God's own interpretive statement: 'For I have broken Moab like an undesirable vessel, declares the LORD.' The *keli* (vessel) of verse 11 — undisturbed, unchanged, flavor intact — is now the same *keli* of verse 38, shattered because it was *ein chephets* — an undesirable, worthless jar. The metaphor has come full circle. The vessel that refused to be emptied and refined has been discarded entirely.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hagah* (to moan, v. 31) is elsewhere used of the sound of a dove (Isaiah 38:14) or of meditating on the Torah (Psalm 1:2) — a low, continuous, internal sound. *Chalil* (flute, v. 36) is associated with both mourning (Matthew 9:23 LXX equivalent) and joy; here unambiguously mourning. *Chephets* (desired/desirable, v. 38, negated) is the same root as 'delightful' in Isaiah 62:4 — a vessel in which no delight remains."
