        "excerpt": "Behold, one will fly swiftly like an eagle and spread out his wings against Moab.",
        "body": "The oracle's final movement returns to announcement after the lament, but with a new image: the eagle. In Deuteronomy 28:49, Moses warned Israel that covenant disobedience would bring 'a nation from afar... that will swoop down like an eagle.' That curse-covenant eagle, originally aimed at Israel, is here redirected at Moab. The conqueror who comes against Moab (almost certainly Babylon under Nebuchadnezzar) is God's eagle — not an autonomous predator but a commissioned instrument. The irony for any Israelite reader is pointed: the very punishment warned against in the Torah for covenant rebellion is now executed on the neighbor who had scorned Israel's punishment.\n\nVerses 41–42 execute the verdict with finality. Kirioth (one of Moab's principal cities) is captured; the strongholds are seized; the hearts of the mighty men of Moab 'will be like the heart of a woman in labor' — the standard Old Testament image for the complete dissolution of military courage (cf. Isaiah 13:8; Jeremiah 6:24; 22:23). The contrast with verse 14 ('we are mighty warriors') is total. Self-assessed military valor evaporates under the divine gaze. Verse 42 then delivers the formal summary: 'Moab will be destroyed from being a people because he has become arrogant toward the LORD.' This is the chapter's theological thesis in its most compressed form — eleven Hebrew words that link national destruction to the precise sin of pride toward God.\n\nThe terror-pit-snare sequence of verses 43–44 draws on Isaiah 24:17–18, embedding the Moab oracle within the broader cosmic judgment framework of Isaiah's apocalypse. The echoing of canonical prophecy is deliberate: Moab's fall is not an isolated geopolitical event but a localized instance of the universal pattern by which God's holiness dismantles every arrogant human structure. Verse 44's 'year of their punishment' (*shenat pequddatam*) frames the event as a divinely calibrated visitation — *pequddah* carries the sense of a scheduled accounting, a day that has been set aside on the divine calendar. The conqueror arrives on time.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nesher* (eagle, v. 40) is the great eagle/griffon vulture, the largest raptor in the ancient Levant — used consistently in OT prophecy for swift, overwhelming military conquest (Deuteronomy 28:49; Habakkuk 1:8; Ezekiel 17:3). *Pequddah* (punishment/visitation, v. 44) is from *paqad* — to visit, to reckon with, to muster for review. The year of *paqad* is the year God arrives to settle the account."
