        "excerpt": "Yet I will restore the fortunes of Moab in the latter days, declares the LORD. Thus far the judgment on Moab.",
        "body": "A single verse at the chapter's close reverses the trajectory of everything that preceded it. After 46 verses of comprehensive, unrelenting judgment — the most extensive oracle against a single foreign nation in the entire book of Jeremiah — the oracle's final word is restoration. 'Yet I will restore the fortunes of Moab in the latter days, declares the LORD.' The Hebrew *shavat shevut* (restore the fortunes/reverse the captivity) is the standard Jeremianic vocabulary for eschatological reversal (30:3, 18; 31:23; 32:44; 33:7, 11, 26). Its application to Moab is theologically radical.\n\nThe identical promise structure appears in 49:6 for Ammon and 49:39 for Elam, suggesting that the Oracles Against the Nations in Jeremiah 46–51 are not simple pronouncements of terminal condemnation but of temporal judgment held within a larger eschatological mercy. The judgment is real, total, and historically executed — Moab was in fact devastated by Nebuchadnezzar and eventually absorbed into surrounding populations. But the theological account does not close with the historical catastrophe. The God who 'restores the fortunes' of Judah (31:23) is the same God who will restore the fortunes of Moab 'in the latter days.'\n\nOrthodox scholars divide on the nature of this restoration. Premillennial interpreters, following the plain sense of 'latter days' (*acharit hayamim*) and the precedent of other specific national restorations in Ezekiel 16:53–55, expect a literal eschatological restoration of peoples in the Moabite geographical region within God's end-time purposes. Amillennial and postmillennial readers, drawing on Paul's argument in Romans 4:16–17 and Ephesians 2:11–13, see the promise fulfilled in the inclusion of Moabite-descended peoples within the new covenant community through faith in Christ — Ruth the Moabitess becoming the ancestress of David and thus of Jesus (Matthew 1:5) as an anticipatory fulfillment. Both readings agree on the governing theological claim: God's last word about nations, as about individuals, is not condemnation but the possibility of restoration through His sovereign mercy.\n\nThe colophon 'Thus far the judgment on Moab' closes the literary unit with formal precision, marking the careful editorial organization of the Oracles Against the Nations. The scribe — whether Baruch or a later editor — signals that what has been read is a distinct, bounded unit within a larger collection. But the positioning of the restoration promise *inside* the colophon and *after* the judgment is not accidental. Mercy brackets wrath. The final utterance in the oracle is *neum YHWH* — 'declares the LORD' — staking the restoration on the same divine authority that staked the judgment."
